<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,460,788]" box="[151,276,460,486]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,460,788]" box="[151,374,503,529]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Wingspan: 
<quantity box="[284,369,503,529]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,460,788]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Transverse lines: black, suffused with brown; basal, antemedial, postmedial, and subterminal lines well marked, with black spot by costa: terminal line marked by black elongated dots.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,460,788]" box="[151,478,632,658]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Reniform: elongated, black.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,460,788]" box="[151,366,675,701]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Hindwing: brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,460,788]" box="[151,515,718,744]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Underside: unicolorous brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,460,788]" box="[151,364,762,788]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Abdomen: brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" box="[151,353,848,874]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Female genitalia.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" box="[151,452,891,917]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Ovipositor: quadrangular.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" box="[151,900,934,960]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Anterior apophyses: length equal to that of posterior apophyses.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" box="[151,966,974,1003]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[165,177,974,988]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
abdominal segment: very narrow, ventrally fused with 7 
<superScript attach="left" box="[841,853,974,988]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
segment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
7 
<superScript attach="left" box="[165,177,1017,1031]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
abdominal segment: heavily sclerotised; position of ostium in middle of segment; two large, hollow, triangular flaps anteroventrally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[165,177,1103,1117]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
segment: posterior part of segment heavily sclerotised and fused to 7 
<superScript attach="left" box="[989,1001,1103,1117]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
segment; anterior part of 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1318,1330,1103,1117]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
segment less heavily sclerotised – similar to rest of abdomen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" box="[151,1236,1193,1219]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Antrum: relatively long and large, tapered, coiling, heavily sclerotised, 6 X longer that wide.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" box="[151,842,1236,1262]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Ductus bursae: membranous, 3 X as long as corpus bursae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,848,1305]" box="[151,439,1279,1305]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Corpus bursae: globular.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1012,1365,1434]" box="[151,412,1365,1391]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1012,1365,1434]" box="[151,1012,1408,1434]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
The female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fibiger" authorityYear="2007" box="[431,562,1408,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Tolpia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis box="[431,562,1408,1433]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">T. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unique in the shape of the antrum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
